                                    <watches>4</watches>
                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14097364" author="snazy" created="Thu, 14 Aug 2014 18:45:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;According to &lt;a href=&quot;http://pypi.python.org/pypi/readline:&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://pypi.python.org/pypi/readline:&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Mac OS X, do not ship with GNU readline installed. The readline extension module in the standard library of Mac &quot;system&quot; Python uses NetBSD&apos;s editline (libedit) library instead, which is a readline replacement with a less restrictive software license.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, you can install it with the command:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;sudo easy_install readline
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(Found on &lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8884001/python-2-7-with-mac-osx-lion-fn-delete-and-control-r&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8884001/python-2-7-with-mac-osx-lion-fn-delete-and-control-r&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14097494" author="jmckenzie" created="Thu, 14 Aug 2014 19:32:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I added a warning to cqlsh on Windows if you run without the pyreadline dependency - might be worth considering on OSX as well.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14097554" author="snazy" created="Thu, 14 Aug 2014 20:13:07 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=joshuaMcKenzie&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;joshuaMcKenzie&quot;&gt;joshuaMcKenzie&lt;/a&gt; good point.&lt;br/&gt;
Added patches for 2.0 and 2.1.&lt;br/&gt;
2.0 patch also backports the Windows test.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14097570" author="jmckenzie" created="Thu, 14 Aug 2014 20:20:19 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Windows portion of the patches lgtm.  Good call on backporting it to 2.0 - no reason not to while we&apos;re here.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14098989" author="jbellis" created="Fri, 15 Aug 2014 19:38:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=iamaleksey&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;iamaleksey&quot;&gt;iamaleksey&lt;/a&gt; to review&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14100032" author="iamaleksey" created="Sun, 17 Aug 2014 18:20:44 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Won&apos;t do. Pretty sure you can configure libedit to enable recursive search, the proper way, instead of throwing a warning to install readline.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We didn&apos;t add libedit support to cqlsh for nothing. &lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="14100068" author="snazy" created="Sun, 17 Aug 2014 19:12:03 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;configure libedit to enable recursive search&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;nope - neither &lt;tt&gt;bind ^R em-inc-search-prev&lt;/tt&gt; in &lt;tt&gt;&amp;#126;/.editrc&lt;/tt&gt; nor &lt;tt&gt;readline.parse_and_bind(&quot;bind ^R em-inc-search-prev&quot;)&lt;/tt&gt; in &lt;tt&gt;&amp;#126;/.pystartup&lt;/tt&gt; or in &lt;tt&gt;cqlsh&lt;/tt&gt; work.&lt;br/&gt;
Recommendation on &lt;a href=&quot;https://pypi.python.org/pypi/readline&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://pypi.python.org/pypi/readline&lt;/a&gt; is to &lt;cite&gt;As the alternatives to GNU readline do not have fully equivalent functionality, it is useful to add proper readline support to these platforms.&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14100091" author="iamaleksey" created="Sun, 17 Aug 2014 20:09:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It does work for me (had to brew uninstall python just to verify that it works).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14100113" author="snazy" created="Sun, 17 Aug 2014 21:09:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Sure you don&apos;t have a readline in /Library/Python/2.7/site-packages ?&lt;br/&gt;
What does &lt;tt&gt;print readline._&lt;em&gt;doc&lt;/em&gt;_&lt;/tt&gt; tell on your machine?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14100120" author="iamaleksey" created="Sun, 17 Aug 2014 21:19:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yes, I&apos;m sure. See the attached screenshots. Also &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-3597&quot; title=&quot;cqlsh: use libedit when readline isn&amp;#39;t available, if possible&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;CASSANDRA-3597&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;CASSANDRA-3597&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14101053" author="JIRAUSER308715" created="Mon, 18 Aug 2014 18:43:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;7577-proper.txt works fine for me and I do not have readline.  The 7577-2.0.txt prints out the warning saying I don&apos;t have it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;+1 on the fix&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14101089" author="iamaleksey" created="Mon, 18 Aug 2014 19:03:01 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Committed, thanks.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14101917" author="snazy" created="Tue, 19 Aug 2014 06:21:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;confirmed: works&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14101920" author="snazy" created="Tue, 19 Aug 2014 06:24:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;For the records: If someone complains about invalid/strange char sequences &lt;tt&gt;&lt;br class=&quot;atl-forced-newline&quot; /&gt;040&lt;/tt&gt; in its history: This happens when switching between libedit and GNU readline. E.g. &lt;tt&gt;select\040*\040from\040system.schema_functions;&lt;/tt&gt; instead of &lt;tt&gt;select * from system.schema_functions;&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
